Joins — the types, the syntax, and the duplicate-column trap.

The method is dataframe-one dot join, with a second dataframe, an on-condition, and a how. There are six how-values worth knowing. Inner, which is the default, keeps rows where the key matches on both sides. Left, right, and full — the outer joins — keep all rows from one side, or both, and null-fill the missing side. Left-semi keeps rows from the left that have a match, but adds none of the right side's columns. Left-anti keeps rows from the left that have no match. And cross gives you the full cartesian product — use it with caution.

Now, there are two ways to name the join key, and the trap lives right here. The first way is a string — join with the key name in quotes — and you use this when both sides share the column name. Spark then de-duplicates the join column for you. The second way is a boolean expression — dataframe-one dot x equals dataframe-two dot y — and you use this when the names differ. In that case, both columns survive in the result.

Here is the trap. If you use the expression form on columns that have the same name — dataframe-one dot k equals dataframe-two dot k — the result ends up with two columns both called k. So any later select of k raises the error, reference k is ambiguous. The fix is to use the string form whenever the names match.

And one more note. Joins use null-unsafe equality by default, so null keys never match. If you genuinely need null keys to match each other, use the equals-null-safe operator.
